06559nam a22007095i 9780773558199DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735581997 a10.1515/97807735581992doi  a(DE-B1597)657225  a(OCoLC)1080220662  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1034.2 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a327.7122300aUndiplomatic History :bThe New Study of Canada and the World /ced. by Asa McKercher, Philip Van Huizen. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b5 images, 1 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRethinking Canada in the World ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTable and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tUndiplomatic History: Rethinking Canada and the World -- tEarly Dominion Relations -- tThe Politics of Sanctuary: John Surratt, the Catholic Church, and the US Civil War -- tMaking Time: Transnational Networks and the Establishment of Standard Time in Canada and Beyond, 1867–1905 -- tRethinking Religion's Role in Canadian Transnational Relations -- tEnvironment and Health -- tNatural Security: Canada-US Environmental Diplomacy -- tSpreading the Gospel of Natural Birth: Canadian Contributions to an International Medical Movement, 1945–60 -- tDecolonization and Liberation -- tJameel's Journal: Jim Peters, Anti-Orientalism, and Arab Decolonization in 1960s Canada -- tInternational Development and the State in Question: Liberal Internationalism, the New Left, and Canadian University Service Overseas in Tanzania, 1963–1977 -- tMaking Global Citizens? Canadian Women at the World Conference of the International Women's Year, Mexico City 1975 -- tCold War and Peace -- tDancing into Hearts and Minds: Canadian Ballet Exchanges with the Communist World, 1956–76 -- tThe Elephant in the Room: Rethinking Cruise Missile Testing and Pierre Trudeau's Peace Mission -- tCold War Endings: The Canadian Peace Congress and the Transnational Peace Movement, 1977–91 -- tHuman Rights, Corporate Rights -- tCanadian Corporate Social Irresponsibility: A History -- tLegislating Hate: Canada, the UN, and the Push to Ban Hate Propaganda, 1960–70 -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the field of Canadian history underwent major shifts in the 1990s, international history became marginalized and the focus turned away from foreign affairs. Over the past decade, however, the study of Canada and the world has been revitalized. Undiplomatic History charts these changes, bringing together leading and emerging historians of Canadian international and transnational relations to take stock of recent developments and to outline the course of future research. Following global trends in the wider historiography, contributors explore new lenses of historical analysis – such as race, gender, political economy, identity, religion, and the environment – and emphasize the relevance of non-state actors, including scientists, athletes, students, and activists. The essays in this volume challenge old ways of thinking and showcase how an exciting new generation of historians are asking novel questions about Canadians' interactions with people and places beyond the country's borders. From human rights to the environment, and from medical internationalism to transnational feminism, Undiplomatic History maps out a path toward a vibrant and inclusive understanding of what constitutes Canadian foreign policy in an age of global connectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aBangarth, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColbourn, Susan